getting out of oceanography. One quick question. 
Do you think that oceanographers are more

26:34.010 --> 26:40.418
inclined to be generalists than, let's say, 
specialists?

26:44.463 --> 26:45.844
Yes, I feel so. And I feel this is very natural. We 
are still following what was laid down in scripts

26:49.909 --> 26:56.237
years ago as to the curriculum in the early years. 
And this by its very nature indicates that if

26:56.757 --> 27:07.628
you're going to understand the ocean as a system, 
you've got to know something about all aspects of

26:56.757 --> 27:07.628
the ocean. The answer, therefore, is that those 
who have come through the oceanographic

27:08.689 --> 27:17.959
curriculum generally are more inclined to a broad 
view. Those who have come from engineering,

27:18.479 --> 27:23.845
however, tend to be highly specialized. And we see 
this in this department, even. And you see it

27:27.745 --> 27:33.632
almost in every major institution where 
engineers have entered the field.

27:35.174 --> 27:48.891
So that I would say, though, that those who go 
through oceanography as a curriculum tend to be

27:35.174 --> 27:48.891
much broader in their perspective than those 
who've entered from a single discipline. Just

27:48.911 --> 27:51.013
happened, my training was very broad. And so it was 
natural that I should come there. But I put out a

27:55.259 --> 28:03.191
little paper on currents because I couldn't find 
anybody who would know anything about the

27:55.259 --> 28:03.191
currents in the bottom. The time I wrote that 
paper, there weren't many who believed there were

28:03.211 --> 28:08.339
any currents in the bottom of the Gulf of Mexico. 
Here, for example, I did something with geology

28:08.579 --> 28:15.550
because I needed to know something about that 
aspect. Go ahead with your question, maybe. No,

